      <field name="fulltext">EASTER BELLS. Glad Easter bells, Strong brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries; On ether seas Of boundless space, Their rippling place, Your notes lost echoes, keep and trace, Eternal as eternities. Oh Easter bells, Strong brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries! With Teuton runes, On low sand dunes, Where chilly moons pale blooms supplied, And north winds sighed, At Southern feasts, With flower-crowned priests, And suns like wine to men and beasts, By seas as blue and bright as skies, Rang Easter bells, Strong brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries! The East, the West, With sign and test, Who loved Christ best, held wordy fray To set the day; Achaian, Gaul, Popes, prelates, all, For life and death, to stand or fall. They said the sun danced in the skies, At Easter bells, Strong brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries! In wilderness, Through storm and stress, Faithful no less, the hermits sang, Their joy-psalms rang From councils grim, The Paschal hymn Pealed out in old cathedrals grim; The notes climbed mingled to the skies, With Easter bells, Loud brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries. Meantime, each Spring, Sweet blossoming, Out-heralding all feud and strife, Revealing life, By year, by year, Near and more near, Brought Christ and swept men's hearts from fear; New gladness in the later skies; At Easter bells, Glad brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries. Gone feud and fray! Faded away, Forgot to-day, as glad we kneel, With prayers that heal; The earth is old; Clear-eyed and bold, Faith sees her way and keeps her hold, Christ risen shines in darkest skies; Ring Easter bells! Strong brazen bells, Sweet silver bells of centuries!</field>
